    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-10-28T05:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-10-28T05:57:00-05:00" n="224"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d224">
                <head>224. Telegram From the Ambassador in Vietnam (<persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                        type="from">Lodge</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                        State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d224fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 26 <gloss target="#t_S1"
                            >S</gloss> VIET. Secret; Immediate; Eyes Only. The source text is <gloss
                            target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> Station telegram 2003 from Saigon sent to
                        the Department of State eyes only for <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HRJ1"
                            >Hilsman</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_HTL1">Hughes</persName>.
                        Also sent to the Department of Defense eyes only for <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GRL1"
                            >Gilpatric</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TGMD1">Taylor</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_KMGVH1">Krulak</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BWP1">William Bundy</persName>; to the White House eyes only
                        for <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">McGeorge Bundy</persName>; and repeated to
                        Honolulu eyes only for <persName corresp="#p_FAHD1">Felt</persName> and to
                            <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> eyes only for <persName
                            corresp="#p_MCJA1">McCone</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CLGMS1"
                            >Carter</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_HR1"
                        >Helms</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1963-10-28T18:57:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 28, 1963—6:57 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Addressees of this message are as suggested in <gloss target="#t_CAS1"
                            >CAS</gloss> Washington [<hi rend="italic">document number not
                            declassified</hi>].<note n="2" xml:id="d224fn2">Not found.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>At the airport 0700 Monday, leading <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                        officials were gathered to say goodbye to President <persName
                            corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName>, who was taking me off on a trip.
                        General <persName corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName> sought me out and asked
                        me whether Conein was authorized to speak for me. I said that he was.
                            <persName corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName> then said that whatever was
                        done must be thoroughly Vietnamese and that the U.S. should not interfere or
                        try to stimulate a coup.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>I said that I agreed; the U.S. wanted no satellites; we would not thwart.
                        I asked how soon action could be expected. He said, we are not ready yet. He
                        then added: Army has lost its drive (in French “allant”); we must win before
                        you Americans leave. We cannot do it with this government, we must,
                        therefore, get a government with which we can win now. I said keep me
                        informed and let me see your plans.<note n="3" xml:id="d224fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_DON1">Don</persName>, in Our Endless War, p. 98,
                            recounts this airport conversation with <persName corresp="#p_LHCJ1"
                                >Lodge</persName> in almost identical terms.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Unless you object, in the interests of maximum security, I propose to
                        limit messages on this subject to myself and the <gloss target="#t_CAS1"
                            >CAS</gloss> ACOS. Others will be given access on a strict need to know
                        basis.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
